irginia gov Virginia Gov Commonwealth of Virginia information online http www firstgov gov FirstGov Gov Federal and State information online Default asp Department of Environmental Engineering Resource Protection Areas Fact Sheets Issued Chesterfield County has issued a Fact Sheet on Resource Protection Areas or RPAs RPAs are the buffers or corridors of environmentally sensitive lands that lie alongside or near the shorelines of streams rivers and other water bodies The Fact Sheets which are being sent to communities throughout Chesterfield contain information on how the RPAs function to protect the quality of our waters They also discuss activities that are permitted and not permitted and list practical ways homeowners can restore RPAs that have been previously cleared Our community is one of many in the county with an RPA running through it If you have already received a Fact Sheet in the mail and have any questions you are encouraged to contact Joan Salvati Chesterfield County s Water Quality Administrator at 751 4665 RPAs filter pollutants out of stormwater runoff prevent erosion and perform other important ecological functions Because of the environmental sensitivity of RPAs the county s Chesapeake Bay Preservation Ordinance requires that these areas be kept in their naturally vegetated condition The only land uses permitted are redevelopment and water dependent facilities such as docks and piers With the introduction of this Fact Sheet citizens whose property contains an RPA are encouraged to protect these areas by leaving them in their naturally vegetated condition Doing so will help reduce pollutants entering our nearby stream The county has produced the Fact Sheets with a grant from the Chesapeake Bay Local Assistance Department Six other Fact Sheets addressing a variety of water quality issues are available in the Water Quality Section s offices at 6806 W Krause Road Chesterfield County complex Download the chesapeake pdf Water Quality Watch Chesapeake Bay